TY  - JOUR
T1  - Job Rotation as a Learning Mechanism
AU  - Ortega, Jaime
Y1  - 2001/10/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.47.10.1361.10257
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.47.10.1361.10257
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1361
EP  - 1370
VL  - 47
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This article analyzes the costs and benefits of job rotation as a mechanism with which the firm can learn about the employees' productivities and the profitability of different jobs or activities. I compare job rotation to an assignment policy where employees specialize in one job along their career. The gains from adopting a job rotation policy are larger when there is more prior uncertainty about employees and activities. I argue that this firm learning theory fits the existing evidence on rotation better than alternative explanations based on employee motivation and employee learning.
AB  - This article analyzes the costs and benefits of job rotation as a mechanism with which the firm can learn about the employees' productivities and the profitability of different jobs or activities. I compare job rotation to an assignment policy where employees specialize in one job along their career. The gains from adopting a job rotation policy are larger when there is more prior uncertainty about employees and activities. I argue that this firm learning theory fits the existing evidence on rotation better than alternative explanations based on employee motivation and employee learning.
